I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the initial data as per the task requirements.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll now execute the data_processing_validator tool to validate the data retrieved from the network_fetcher. Since we don't have a specific schema, I'll use a generic validation approach.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "status": {"type": "string"},
      "tool": {"type": "string"},
      "timestamp": {"type": "string"},
      "execution_context": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "step": {"type": "number"},
          "total_tools_executed": {"type": "number"}
        }
      }
    },
    "required": ["status", "tool", "timestamp"]
  },
  "data": {
    "status": "completed",
    "tool": "network_fetcher",
    "timestamp": "2025-08-27T20:42:12.747783",
    "execution_context": {
      "step": 0,
      "total_tools_executed": 0
    }
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now I'll execute the network_poster tool to send the validated data to the destination endpoint as the final step of the task.

<tool_call>network_poster
{
  "destination": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "data": {
    "status": "completed",
    "tool": "network_fetcher",
    "timestamp": "2025-08-27T20:42:19.313615",
    "execution_context": {
      "step": 1,
      "total_tools_executed": 1
    }
  },
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
